expectation_vs_outcome:
I initially found this task less satisfying than my first two attempts. I think this is because while I have a basic understanding of the system, different parameters seeem to feed into the same outcome unless rules are followed. 

Despite this I really enjoyed the final playback as there were lots of interesting audio and visual outputs which were partially planned but also unexpected.

I had no idea what it would be like so no expectations aside from faster to slower / more > less light. I had forgotten that compaitble colours made compatible tones which is perhaps why I didn't make a 'pleasing' chord/ sound. I did like the way it looked.
I enjoyed the looping rhythms both visually and in sound

I couldn't imagine what it would be like from looking at the light pattern but I liked the sound and the correlations. the nature-like patterns and the shift in feel when adding a new colour, then the chaos broke out but managed to regain composure by the end.

param_other: Set an initial set of parameters giving rhythmic pattern that felt the right proportion of 'busy' and then changed scale notes.
interference_notes: There were moments (when reviewing the piece) when I was surprised by disonance in note tones despite colour combinations produced.
expectation_vs_outcome: The result was suprisingly interesting/mesmerising, I could feel my brain try to work out the pattern as well as surprise/'delight' as new patterns of chord tones and colour combinations emerged and changed throughout the piece. The colours on the video were not as easily discernable as when looking at the physical instrument. As I am a musician - my association felt more like light was accompanying the sound, although with longer exposure to the instrument this may change.

interference_notes: Length of light activity was misleading for tone length which was shorter and did not match.
expectation_vs_outcome:
I expected the sound to be more dissonant than it was (i.e. a good matching between tones and light combinations - constructive intereference), this is probably related to the lights being kept on for longer than the associated sound was playing. At times (especially from the middle of the piece to the end) I did not find much association between light duration and note duration - destructive intereference.
The shared tonality was surprisingly consonant when colours where matched. When there were dissonant tones playing at the same time, it was more 'interesting' in the sound modality than in the lights modality (e.g. introduction of a green to predominantly purple/red colour combinations).

Overall, the creation of the piece this time was more intuition driven, and I was not 'thinking' about what would sound good given my background music theory knowledge.

interference_notes: It felt like at times of low sound activity there were more lights active than expected, although as I said, this was a positive in this instance rather than a negative contributor to experiencing the piece. It was less clear why small changes in scale tones used led to large cascades in near-neighbour activation. Essentially it felt like a set of stable ('solid') states separated by high disorganisation in the states ('gas/liquid' states).
expectation_vs_outcome:
The light modality was more organised than I expected for the majority of the piece, revealing repeated spatial patterns when tones had more pleasing scale intervals. It felt like the pattern of light placements added an extra dimension/dynamicism to the piece, as they shifted between ordered spatially repeating patterns, separated by times of high activity/randomness that corresponded to dissonance and (at those times) overwhelming sound arrangements. 
The spatial extent of the light patterns (how many lights were active at any one time) were surprising given how few notes were playing (between shifts) - this actually added to the experience as one note playing activated multiple lights it created something more interesting to look at.

interference_notes: No, however it is possible to witness properties and not understand where they come from or how to control them, within this time frame.

This is satisflying as someone who does not consider themselves musical. The visual patterns help reveal the relationships between notes.

interference_notes: THe visual display felt much more crowded but less chaotic  - more structure perhaps? I was surprised by the lines runnig across the deck, and at one point there was a visual walk around the deck that I did not expect and did not hear in the sound whilst it was happening.
expectation_vs_outcome: The visuals had a greater range of dense to sparse, and a greater range of patterning than expected. It seems like there are more rules or instances of notes visually than aurally. The visuals felt more graspable than my recollection of my control of the sounds but this might be reflection vs action.

interference_notes: The visual pattern did not match any auditory chonchordancy / harmony in any way that I would have predicted - they patterns of visuals and audio seem very separate. In addition, the pure tone perhaps meant that I could not hear the full complex nature of the sound that was clearly present and visible - perhaps because different octaves of the same note starting at the same time sounded as one. I could hear flurries of consecutive notes and perhaps different notes that coincided. I would be very interested to hear the outcome if these notes were more distinguishable, and likely would produce a much less busy piece!
expectation_vs_outcome: The business of the sound did not seem to match the pattern or crowqding of the visuals. A number of sparse visuals sounded as busy as a previously very active visual. The visual patterning seemed to match dischordant sounds. and in some cases vice versa - a pleasant sound matching no visual pattern. A big mismatch overall.

interference_notes: I am beginning to see why having neighbouring notes available results in simple repeating patterns and also dischordant sounds, and why having more harmony constrains the visuals under some game of life conditions, something about having the notes far enough away from each other meaning they are poor / unrelated neighbours. I think if I had better music theory I would understand this differently.
expectation_vs_outcome: Less obvious visual structure than I expected but a stronger match between what I planned and what happened, and I feel like I am beginning to see a different and less obvious visual structure and how that relates to the sounds/notes. The two modalities are starting to feel linked in a way I didn't experience before. I had some inkling of this while playing but could see some impacts more clearly and unexpectedly in the review.
